  "text": "It remains to find the spatial scale σ for the Laplacian. To adapt to the data, we leverage 1D persistent homology from TDA [CITATION_1] to find the scale at which the primary topological feature -the single cycle -exists. Specifically, we compute the 1D Vietoris Rips Filtration on our sliding window data Z, which tracks equivalence classes of loops, known as homology classes [31] . The algorithm returns a so-called persistence diagram, a multiset of points on a 2D birth/death grid, with each point corresponding to a loop class. The birth value b i indicates the scale at which the i th loop class forms, and the death value d i indicates the scale at which that class no longer exists. The difference d i − b i is known as the persistence of the i th class. For our scenario, one point in the diagram should have a much larger persistence than the others (e.g. Figure 1 ) [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and this ideally reflects the single cycle of motion that we seek. We take our scale to be αb i + (1 − α)d i for the largest d i − b i , where α ∈ [0, 1] is a parameter which will be explored experimentally in Section 3.",
